INSERT INTO `Texts` VALUES (36,NULL,144,'The expedition began here in St. Louis, Missouri, on May 14, 1804, where Clark, along with 30 other men, met Lewis and ten other members of the group.',NULL,'2024-10-08 16:21:20'),(41,NULL,148,'From November 1804 to April 1805, the expedition built and stayed at Fort Mandan near the present-day town of Washburn. Here, they made contact with the Mandan and Hidatsa tribes and recruited Sacagawea as a guide',NULL,'2024-10-08 17:00:43'),(43,NULL,149,'In September 1805, the Corps crossed the Bitterroot Mountains via Lolo Pass. This grueling journey took them through harsh terrain and severe weather, nearly leading to starvation',NULL,'2024-10-08 17:03:35'),(44,NULL,152,'In June 1805, the Corps encountered the Great Falls of the Missouri, a massive waterfall that required a difficult 17 mile portage. It took nearly a month to navigate around the falls',NULL,'2024-10-08 17:10:45'),(53,NULL,150,'After reaching the Pacific Ocean in November 1805, the expedition built Fort Clatsop near the mouth of the Columbia River and spent the winter of 1805-1806 there',NULL,'2024-10-08 17:14:24'),(55,NULL,151,'On July 25, 1806, during the return journey, William Clark carved his name into Pompeys Pillar, a sandstone formation near the Yellowstone River. This is one of the few surviving physical marks left by the expedition',NULL,'2024-10-08 17:28:08'),(56,NULL,154,'George Washington was born on February 22, 1732, at his family\'s plantation on Pope\'s Creek in Westmoreland County, Virginia. The site is now part of the George Washington Birthplace National Monument, which encompasses 551 acres of land. This area was central to one of the earliest efforts to memorialize George Washington during the celebration of his bicentennial birth anniversary in 1932.\n\nThe park offers a glimpse into the early life of Washington and the history of the Washington family, who lived on this land for seven generations. It\'s a place of both historical significance and natural beauty, with opportunities for visitors to explore the grounds and learn more about the first President of the United States.',NULL,'2024-10-15 14:33:28'),(57,NULL,155,'John Adams Birthplace in Quincy, Massachusetts, is a significant historical site. The modest saltbox house offers a glimpse into the early life of the second U.S. president and a Founding Father. This well-preserved landmark captures the essence of 18th-century New England and the formative years of a future president. Visitors can explore the simple yet poignant rooms where Adams developed his early views and values, shaping the leadership that would later help forge the nation. This site, along with the nearby Adams National Historical Park, provides a comprehensive look at the Adams family\'s lasting impact on American history.',NULL,'2024-10-15 16:18:44'),(59,NULL,156,'Thomas Jefferson was born on April 13, 1743, at the family\'s Shadwell Plantation in the British Colony of Virginia. Shadwell is located in Albemarle County, Virginia, and a notable historic site. Although the original house was destroyed by fire, the location remains a key piece of American heritage. Jefferson, the third U.S. president and principal author of the Declaration of Independence, spent his early years here. The site offers insight into the formative environment that shaped one of the nation\'s most influential Founding Fathers. Visitors can explore the grounds and nearby Monticello, Jefferson\'s renowned estate, to gain a deeper understanding of his legacy and contributions to the fledgling United States.',NULL,'2024-10-15 16:30:56'),(61,NULL,158,'James Monroe was born on April 28, 1758, at Monroe Hall in Westmoreland County, Virginia. Monroe, the fifth U.S. president, spent his early years in this scenic region, which played a crucial role in shaping his character and values. The site offers a glimpse into the pastoral life of the 18th century and the upbringing of a future president who would later contribute significantly to the nation\'s development. Visitors can explore the area to gain insight into Monroe\'s early influences and the environment that helped mold his leadership qualities.',NULL,'2024-10-15 16:49:51'),(62,NULL,159,'John Quincy Adams was born on July 11, 1767, in Braintree, Massachusetts, now part of Quincy. As the son of John Adams, the second U.S. president, John Quincy Adams grew up immersed in the early political and revolutionary fervor that shaped the nation. His birthplace, a modest New England home at 141 Franklin Street, provided a nurturing environment that influenced his remarkable diplomatic and political career. This historic saltbox house, built in 1716, carries significant historical value as it is the place where one of the key figures in American history spent his early years. Visitors to this site can gain insight into the early life and legacy of the sixth U.S. president, who played a crucial role in American history, both as a statesman and an advocate for antislavery',NULL,'2024-10-15 17:01:58'),(63,NULL,160,'Andrew Jackson was born on March 15, 1767, in a rustic area near the North Carolina and South Carolina border. The exact location of his birth is debated, but one of the likely spots is commemorated by the Andrew Jackson Birthplace monument. This monument marks where the George McCamie cabin once stood, built from rough boulders sourced from the cabin\'s chimney foundation. A small marble plaque and the Daughters of the American Revolution symbol are set into the base. Above this, a rough-hewn granite slab stands tall with a relief of the McCamie cabin and an inscription, though both have suffered vandalism over the years. To visit this secluded monument, one must venture into South Carolina, adding to its allure and historical mystique.',NULL,'2024-10-15 17:08:59'),(64,NULL,161,'Martin Van Buren was born on December 5, 1782, in Kinderhook, New York, a small Dutch community near Albany. The Martin Van Buren National Historic Site preserves his birthplace and offers a glimpse into his early life. Although the original house no longer stands, the site features a visitor center and restored buildings that showcase Van Buren\'s legacy and contributions to American politics',NULL,'2024-10-15 17:21:21'),(65,NULL,162,'William Henry Harrison, the ninth U.S. president, was born on February 9, 1773, at Berkeley Plantation in Charles City County, Virginia. This historic site is notable for being the location where Harrison spent his early years in a prominent Virginia family. The plantation is one of the oldest in America and offers visitors a chance to explore the beautiful grounds and learn about Harrison\'s early life and his journey to becoming president.',NULL,'2024-10-15 17:30:28'),(66,NULL,163,'John Tyler was born on March 29, 1790, at Greenway Plantation in Charles City County, Virginia. This historic site offers a glimpse into Tyler\'s early life in a prominent Virginia family. The plantation, with its beautiful grounds and historic buildings, provides visitors with insight into the upbringing of the tenth U.S. president, who assumed office after the death of William Henry Harrison and is known for his strong support of states rights.',NULL,'2024-10-15 17:40:17'),(96,NULL,167,'James K. Polk was born on November 2, 1795, in Pineville, North Carolina. He is often referred to as the \"dark horse\" president due to his unexpected nomination. Polk oversaw significant territorial expansion during his presidency, including the annexation of Texas, the Oregon Territory, and the acquisition of California following the Mexican-American War. He is also credited with reestablishing an independent treasury system and reducing tariffs. Polk served a single term and chose not to seek re-election, retiring in 1849.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:34:35'),(97,NULL,168,'Zachary Taylor was born on November 24, 1784, in Barboursville, Virginia. A career military man, Taylor earned the nickname \"Old Rough and Ready\" for his leadership in the Mexican-American War. He became the 12th president of the United States but died just 16 months into his presidency on July 9, 1850. His presidency focused on preserving the Union during the rising tensions over slavery, though his unexpected death left many of his plans unfinished.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:35:12'),(100,NULL,169,'Millard Fillmore was born on January 7, 1800, in Moravia, New York. He ascended to the presidency after Zachary Taylor\'s death. Fillmore is most known for signing the Compromise of 1850, which included the controversial Fugitive Slave Act, aimed at calming tensions between the North and South. Though this compromise delayed the Civil War, it heightened tensions regarding slavery. After his presidency, Fillmore unsuccessfully ran for president again in 1856 as the candidate of the Know Nothing Party',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:39:04'),(101,NULL,170,'Franklin Pierce was born on November 23, 1804, in Hillsborough, New Hampshire. Pierce\'s presidency is often remembered for his support of the Kansas-Nebraska Act, which allowed new territories to decide whether to allow slavery through popular sovereignty. This act led to \"Bleeding Kansas,\" a series of violent confrontations between pro-slavery and anti-slavery forces. Pierce\'s pro-Southern stance alienated many in the North, and his presidency is often considered one of the weakest in U.S. history.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:41:30'),(102,NULL,171,'James Buchanan was born on April 23, 1791, in Cove Gap, Pennsylvania. Serving as the 15th president, Buchanan\'s time in office is most remembered for his inability to prevent the secession of Southern states, which led to the Civil War. Despite his vast political experience, Buchanan is often ranked as one of the worst U.S. presidents due to his inaction during this critical period. His efforts to appease both North and South ended in failure, and his presidency is widely criticized.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:47:18'),(103,NULL,172,'Abraham Lincoln was born on February 12, 1809, in Hodgenville, Kentucky. Lincoln led the country through its greatest moral, constitutional, and political crisis: the American Civil War. He preserved the Union, abolished slavery with the Emancipation Proclamation and the 13th Amendment, and modernized the U.S. economy through infrastructure and banking reforms. His assassination on April 14, 1865, shortly after the war\'s end, cemented his legacy as one of the greatest U.S. presidents',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:50:29'),(104,NULL,173,'Andrew Johnson was born on December 29, 1808, in Raleigh, North Carolina. Johnson became president after Lincoln\'s assassination. His presidency was marked by his lenient Reconstruction policies, which allowed Southern states to quickly rejoin the Union without guaranteeing rights for former slaves. His opposition to the Radical Republicans\' plans for Reconstruction led to his impeachment by the House of Representatives, though he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:53:19'),(105,NULL,174,'Ulysses S. Grant was born on April 27, 1822, in Point Pleasant, Ohio. As a leading Union general during the Civil War, Grant secured key victories for the North, most notably at Vicksburg and Appomattox, where Confederate forces surrendered. His presidency focused on Reconstruction and civil rights for African Americans. However, his administration was plagued by numerous scandals involving his political appointees, despite Grant\'s personal integrity.',NULL,'2024-10-22 13:57:11'),(106,NULL,175,'Rutherford B. Hayes was born on October 4, 1822, in Delaware, Ohio. His presidency is best known for the Compromise of 1877, which resolved the disputed 1876 election and effectively ended Reconstruction by withdrawing federal troops from the South. Hayes also worked to reform the civil service and sought to restore the public\'s trust in government after the scandals of the Grant administration. He served one term and did not seek re-election.',NULL,'2024-10-22 14:01:04'),(107,NULL,176,'James A. Garfield was born on November 19, 1831, in Moreland Hills, Ohio. He is remembered for his short presidency, having been shot just four months into his term. Garfield was a strong advocate of civil service reform, aiming to reduce corruption in government appointments. His assassination in 1881 by a disgruntled office-seeker brought attention to the need for reform, eventually leading to the passage of the Pendleton Civil Service Reform Act.',NULL,'2024-10-22 14:04:17'),(108,NULL,178,'Chester A. Arthur was born on October 5, 1829, in Fairfield, Vermont. Arthur\'s presidency is often remembered for his support of the Pendleton Civil Service Act, which reformed the federal government\'s hiring practices by implementing a merit-based system rather than patronage. This act was a significant step towards reducing corruption and improving efficiency in government jobs. Arthur\'s presidency also saw the passage of the Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882, which restricted Chinese immigration. Despite being a former supporter of the spoils system, Arthur\'s advocacy for civil service reform surprised many and helped to distance him from his earlier political affiliations. His presidency is often considered a period of reform and modernization in the federal government',NULL,'2024-10-22 17:30:29'),(109,NULL,179,'Grover Cleveland was born on March 18, 1837, in Caldwell, New Jersey. Cleveland\'s presidency is often remembered for his commitment to political reform and fiscal conservatism. He is the only U.S. president to serve two non-consecutive terms, making him both the 22nd and 24th president. Cleveland\'s first term (1885-1889) was marked by his opposition to high tariffs and his use of the veto power to block unnecessary legislation. His second term (1893-1897) was dominated by the economic challenges of the Panic of 1893, during which he upheld the gold standard and opposed government intervention in the economy. Cleveland\'s dedication to principle over politics earned him a reputation as an honest and principled leader, though his strict fiscal policies were sometimes controversia',NULL,'2024-10-22 17:34:36'),(110,NULL,180,'Benjamin Harrison was born on August 20, 1833, in North Bend, Ohio. Harrison\'s presidency, from 1889 to 1893, is often remembered for his commitment to civil rights and efforts to promote American commerce and industry. He was a Republican and a former senator from Indiana. Harrison\'s administration saw the passage of the McKinley Tariff, which raised duties on imports to protect domestic industries, and the Sherman Antitrust Act, aimed at curbing monopolies. His presidency also included the admission of six new states to the Union. Despite his efforts, Harrison\'s economic policies contributed to the depression that hit the country after he left office. His social and foreign policies, however, were considered visionary and bold',NULL,'2024-10-22 17:40:38'),(111,NULL,181,'William McKinley was born on January 29, 1843, in Niles, Ohio. McKinley\'s presidency, from 1897 to 1901, is often remembered for his leadership during the Spanish-American War. Under his leadership, the United States emerged victorious and acquired several new territories, including Puerto Rico, Guam, and the Philippines, marking the beginning of the U.S. as a global power. McKinley was also known for his support of high protective tariffs, which aimed to shield American industries from foreign competition. His presidency saw economic growth, but it was cut short by his assassination in 1901. McKinley\'s time in office is often seen as a period of expansion and modernization for the United States.',NULL,'2024-10-22 17:45:12'),(131,NULL,184,'Theodore Roosevelt was born on October 27, 1858, at 28 East 20th Street, New York City, New York, which is now the Theodore Roosevelt Birthplace National Historic Site\n\n. Overcoming childhood illness, he embraced a vigorous lifestyle and graduated from Harvard. After personal tragedy, he became a cattle rancher in the Dakota Territory before returning to public service.\n\nRoosevelt gained national fame leading the Rough Riders in the Spanish-American War. He became president in 1901 after McKinley\'s assassination, promoting his \"Square Deal\" policies which targeted trusts, labor rights, and consumer protections. Roosevelt was a pioneering conservationist, setting aside millions of acres for national forests and parks. His foreign policy, \"Big Stick\" diplomacy, emphasized strong military presence and he facilitated the construction of the Panama Canal.\n\nHe earned a Nobel Peace Prize for mediating the Russo-Japanese War. After his presidency, he continued his influence, running as a Progressive in 1912. Roosevelt\'s legacy is a mix of progressive reform, environmental conservation, and strong national leadership. He died on January 6, 1919.',NULL,'2024-10-22 17:50:12'),(139,NULL,189,'Warren G. Harding was born on November 2, 1865, in Corsica (now Blooming Grove), Ohio. Harding\'s presidency, from 1921 to 1923, is often remembered for his promise of a \"return to normalcy\" following World War I. He was a successful newspaper publisher before entering politics, serving in the Ohio State Senate, as lieutenant governor, and later as a U.S. Senator\n\n.\n\nAs president, Harding favored pro-business policies and limited immigration\n. His administration saw the establishment of the Veterans Bureau and the General Accounting Office. However, his presidency was marred by corruption scandals, most notably the Teapot Dome scandal, which involved the secret leasing of federal oil reserves in exchange for bribes\n\n.\n\nHarding\'s sudden death on August 2, 1923, in San Francisco, California, cut his presidency short\n. Despite his initial popularity, the posthumous exposure of corruption significantly tarnished his legacy.',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:00:28'),(145,NULL,193,'Calvin Coolidge was born on July 4, 1872, in Plymouth Notch, Vermont. Known for his quiet demeanor, Coolidge became the 30th President of the United States after the sudden death of Warren G. Harding in 1923. His presidency is often remembered for restoring integrity to the executive branch following the scandals of the Harding administration.\n\nCoolidge was a pro-business conservative who favored tax cuts and limited government spending. His policies contributed to the economic prosperity of the Roaring Twenties, but some argue they also set the stage for the Great Depression. He was known as \"Silent Cal\" for his reserved and frugal nature, which resonated with the American public during a time of rapid social and cultural change.\n\nCoolidge\'s legacy includes his efforts to reduce government corruption and his support for business-friendly policies. He chose not to run for a second full term and retired to Northampton, Massachusetts, where he passed away on January 5, 193',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:07:38'),(147,NULL,199,'Herbert Hoover was born on August 10, 1874, in West Branch, Iowa. He was the first U.S. president born west of the Mississippi River. Hoover was a successful mining engineer and humanitarian before entering politics. He gained fame for his efforts in providing food relief to Europe during and after World War I.\n\nHoover served as the 31st President of the United States from 1929 to 1933. His presidency began just before the onset of the Great Depression, a period of severe economic downturn. Despite his efforts to combat the crisis, including the establishment of public works programs and the Reconstruction Finance Corporation, Hoover\'s policies were widely seen as inadequate. His administration was criticized for its inability to alleviate widespread unemployment and poverty.\n\nHoover\'s legacy is often overshadowed by the economic hardships of the Great Depression, but his earlier humanitarian work and his post-presidential efforts in public service are also significant aspects of his life. He passed away on October 20, 1964, in New ',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:12:57'),(148,NULL,200,'Franklin D. Roosevelt was born on January 30, 1882, in Hyde Park, New York, which is now the Home of Franklin D. Roosevelt National Historic Site. Roosevelt, commonly known as FDR, served as the 32nd President of the United States from 1933 until his death in 1945. He is the only president to have served more than two terms, leading the country through the Great Depression and World War II.\n\nFDR\'s presidency began with his New Deal programs, which aimed to provide relief, recovery, and reform to a nation struggling with economic hardship\n. His first 100 days in office saw an unprecedented level of legislative activity, including the establishment of the Tennessee Valley Authority and Social Security. Roosevelt\'s leadership during World War II was marked by his efforts to support the Allies through programs like Lend-Lease before the U.S. formally entered the war after the attack on Pearl Harbor.\n\nDespite being paralyzed from the waist down due to polio, Roosevelt\'s determination and leadership were unwavering. He communicated directly with the American people through his famous \"fireside chats,\" fostering a sense of connection and trust. FDR\'s legacy includes his role in shaping modern American government and his impact on global politics during a time of unprecedented challenges',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:18:40'),(154,NULL,203,'Harry S. Truman was born on May 8, 1884, in Lamar, Missouri. Truman grew up in Independence, Missouri, and served as a farmer before joining the military during World War I as a captain in the Field Artillery. After the war, he opened a haberdashery in Kansas City with a business partner, but the venture eventually failed.\n\nTruman entered politics and served as a U.S. Senator from Missouri from 1935 to 1945. He became the 33rd President of the United States in 1945 following the death of Franklin D. Roosevelt. Truman led the country through the final stages of World War II and the early years of the Cold War. He is known for his decisive actions, including the decision to use atomic weapons on Japan to hasten the end of the war.\n\nTruman\'s presidency also saw the implementation of the Marshall Plan, which provided aid to rebuild Western Europe after the war, and the Truman Doctrine, which aimed to contain Soviet expansion\n. He also supported the creation of the United Nations and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).\nDespite facing significant challenges, including labor strikes and the beginning of the Korean War, Truman\'s straightforward and decisive leadership style earned him the nickname \"Give \'Em Hell Harry.\" He chose not to run for another term and retired to Independence, Missouri, where he passed away on December 26, 1972',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:30:56'),(155,NULL,205,'Dwight D. Eisenhower was born on October 14, 1890, in Denison, Texas. He grew up in Abilene, Kansas, and graduated from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point in 1915. Eisenhower had a distinguished military career, serving as Supreme Commander of the Allied Expeditionary Force in Europe during World War II. He led the D-Day invasion of Normandy in 1944, which was a turning point in the war against Nazi Germany.\n\nAfter the war, Eisenhower served as President of Columbia University and then as the first Supreme Commander of NATO before entering politics. He was elected as the 34th President of the United States in 1952 and served two terms from 1953 to 1961. His presidency is known for managing Cold War tensions, ending the Korean War, and promoting infrastructure development, including the creation of the Interstate Highway System.\n\nEisenhower\'s administration also saw the strengthening of Social Security and efforts to contain the spread of communism. However, he faced criticism for not fully enforcing the Supreme Court\'s desegregation order in the Brown v. Board of Education case. Eisenhower passed away on March 28, 1969, in Washington, D.C',NULL,'2024-10-22 18:38:01'),(157,NULL,206,'John F. Kennedy, often referred to as JFK, was born on May 29, 1917, in Brookline, Massachusetts. He hailed from the prominent Kennedy family and graduated from Harvard University in 1940. During World War II, he served heroically in the U.S. Navy, earning the Navy and Marine Corps Medal for his actions during the sinking of PT-109. Kennedy began his political career in the U.S. House of Representatives in 1947 and then served as a U.S. Senator from Massachusetts from 1953 to 1960. Elected as the 35th president of the United States in 1960, he was the youngest person elected to the office and the first Roman Catholic president. His presidency included significant events such as the Cuban Missile Crisis, the establishment of the Peace Corps, and advancements in civil rights. Tragically, Kennedy\'s life and presidency were cut short when he was assassinated on November 22, 1963, in Dallas, Texas, a moment that left a profound impact on the nation and the world.',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:07:31'),(160,NULL,207,'Lyndon B. Johnson, often referred to as LBJ, was born on August 27, 1908, in Gillespie County, Texas. He began his political career in the U.S. House of Representatives in 1937 and later served as a U.S. Senator from Texas from 1949 to 1961. Johnson was elected vice president in 1960 and assumed the presidency on November 22, 1963, following the assassination of John F. Kennedy. As the 36th president of the United States, he is known for his ambitious \"Great Society\" programs, which aimed to eliminate poverty and racial injustice. Key achievements of his presidency include the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the Voting Rights Act of 1965, and the establishment of Medicare and Medicaid. However, his presidency was also marked by the escalation of the Vietnam War, which led to widespread protest and controversy. Johnson chose not to seek re-election in 1968 and retired to his ranch in Texas, where he passed away on January 22, 1973\n',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:08:55'),(161,NULL,208,'Richard Milhous Nixon, born on January 9, 1913, in Yorba Linda, California, was the 37th president of the United States. He began his political career in the U.S. House of Representatives in 1947, later served as a U.S. Senator from California, and then became Vice President under Dwight D. Eisenhower from 1953 to 1961. Nixon was elected president in 1968 and re-elected in 1972. His presidency saw significant foreign policy achievements, including the historic opening of diplomatic relations with China and the signing of the Strategic Arms Limitation Talks (SALT) agreement with the Soviet Union. However, Nixon\'s presidency was marred by the Watergate scandal, leading to his resignation on August 8, 1974, to avoid impeachment. He retired from politics and spent his later years writing and engaging in public speaking until his death on April 22, 1994',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:16:16'),(162,NULL,209,'Gerald R. Ford, born on July 14, 1913, in Omaha, Nebraska, became the 38th president of the United States. Originally named Leslie Lynch King Jr., his name was changed after his mother remarried. Ford served in the U.S. Navy during World War II and began his political career in the U.S. House of Representatives, where he served from 1949 to 1973, eventually becoming House Minority Leader. He was appointed vice president in 1973 following Spiro Agnew\'s resignation and assumed the presidency on August 9, 1974, following Richard Nixon\'s resignation amid the Watergate scandal. As president, Ford is known for his controversial pardon of Nixon and efforts to address inflation and economic difficulties. He was defeated by Jimmy Carter in the 1976 presidential election and retired from politics, living the rest of his life in California until his death on December 26, 2006.',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:20:46'),(163,NULL,210,'Jimmy Carter, born on October 1, 1924, in Plains, Georgia, became the 39th president of the United States. Before his presidency, he served as a naval officer and peanut farmer, and later as the governor of Georgia from 1971 to 1975. Elected president in 1976, Carter\'s administration focused on human rights and energy policies. Notable achievements include the Camp David Accords, which brokered peace between Egypt and Israel, and the Panama Canal treaties. However, his presidency faced significant challenges such as the Iran Hostage Crisis and economic issues like inflation. After leaving office in 1981, Carter became known for his humanitarian work, particularly through the Carter Center, and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2002. He continues to be an influential figure in global health, democracy, and peace efforts',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:27:16'),(164,NULL,211,'Ronald Reagan, born on February 6, 1911, in Tampico, Illinois, was the 40th president of the United States. Before his political career, Reagan was a Hollywood actor and president of the Screen Actors Guild. He served as the governor of California from 1967 to 1975. Elected president in 1980, his administration, known for its conservative policies and economic reforms, dubbed \"Reaganomics,\" sought to reduce government spending and taxes. Significant events during his presidency include the end of the Cold War, the Iran-Contra affair, and the appointment of the first female Supreme Court Justice, Sandra Day O\'Connor. Reagan survived an assassination attempt in 1981 and completed two terms in office, leaving in 1989. He passed away on June 5, 2004, after a long battle with Alzheimer\'s disease.',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:32:25'),(165,NULL,212,'George H. W. Bush, born on June 12, 1924, in Milton, Massachusetts, served as the 41st president of the United States. Before his presidency, Bush had a long career in public service: he was a naval aviator during World War II, U.S. congressman, ambassador to the United Nations, director of the CIA, and vice president under Ronald Reagan from 1981 to 1989. Elected president in 1988, his term from 1989 to 1993 was marked by significant events, including the end of the Cold War, the Gulf War, and the signing of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). However, economic recession and breaking his \"no new taxes\" pledge contributed to his defeat in the 1992 election. After leaving office, Bush continued to be active in humanitarian efforts and partnered with former political adversaries for charity work until his death on November 30, 2018.',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:45:41'),(166,NULL,213,'Bill Clinton, born William Jefferson Blythe III on August 19, 1946, in Hope, Arkansas, served as the 42nd president of the United States from 1993 to 2001. Before his presidency, he was the governor of Arkansas and the state\'s attorney general. Clinton\'s presidency was marked by significant economic growth and the longest peacetime economic expansion in American history. He signed into law the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act. However, his administration faced challenges, including the failed attempt at health care reform and the Monica Lewinsky scandal, which led to his impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1998. He was acquitted by the Senate in 1999. After leaving office, Clinton continued his public service through the Clinton Foundation, focusing on global health, economic development, and climate change\n',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:49:50'),(167,NULL,214,'George W. Bush, born on July 6, 1946, in New Haven, Connecticut, is the 43rd president of the United States1. He grew up in Texas and attended Yale University, where he earned a bachelor\'s degree in history in 1968. After serving as an F-102 fighter pilot in the Texas Air National Guard, Bush received an MBA from Harvard Business School in 1975. He later entered the oil industry and co-owned the Texas Rangers baseball team before being elected governor of Texas in 1994.\n\nBush was elected president in 2000, winning a closely contested election that involved a Supreme Court decision to stop a recount in Florida. His presidency was profoundly shaped by the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, which led to the initiation of the \"War on Terror,\" including the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq. Domestically, he signed significant legislation such as the No Child Left Behind Act and the Medicare prescription drug benefit. However, his second term faced challenges, including the financial crisis of 2008 and the controversial handling of Hurricane Katrina.\n\nBush left office in 2009 and has since focused on his presidential library, public speaking, and humanitarian efforts',NULL,'2024-10-23 16:56:52'),(168,NULL,215,'Barack Obama, born on August 4, 1961, in Honolulu, Hawaii, is the 44th president of the United States and the first African American to hold the office. His father, Barack Obama Sr., was a Kenyan economist, and his mother, Ann Dunham, was an anthropologist. After his parents\' separation, Obama spent part of his childhood in Indonesia before returning to Hawaii to live with his maternal grandparents. He attended Punahou School, an elite private school, and later graduated from Columbia University with a degree in political science.\n\nObama moved to Chicago to work as a community organizer and then attended Harvard Law School, where he became the first African American president of the Harvard Law Review. After law school, he returned to Chicago to practice civil rights law and entered politics, serving in the Illinois Senate and the U.S. Senate. He was elected president in 2008, defeating Arizona Senator John McCain.\n\nAs president, Obama\'s administration was marked by significant achievements, including the passage of the Affordable Care Act (ACA), also known as \"Obamacare,\" the killing of Osama bin Laden, and the Iran Nuclear Deal. He also focused on economic recovery following the Great Recession and promoted human rights and environmental policies. Obama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2009 for his efforts to strengthen international diplomacy and cooperation. After leaving office, Obama has continued to be an influential figure through the Obama Foundation and his memoirs, \"Dreams from My Father\" and \"The Audacity of Hope.\"\n',NULL,'2024-10-23 17:06:11'),(169,NULL,216,'Donald Trump, born on June 14, 1946, in Queens, New York, is the 45th president of the United States. Before his presidency, Trump was a businessman and television personality. He graduated from the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania with a degree in economics. Trump took over his family\'s real estate business in 1971, renaming it the Trump Organization and expanding its operations to include skyscrapers, hotels, casinos, and golf courses. He gained fame as the host of the reality TV show \"The Apprentice.\"\n\nTrump was elected president in 2016, defeating Democratic candidate Hillary Clinton. His presidency was marked by significant events such as the implementation of tax cuts, the appointment of three Supreme Court justices, and the renegotiation of trade deals. However, his term was also characterized by controversy, including the investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election and two impeachments by the House of Representatives. Trump left office on January 20, 2021, after losing the 2020 election to Joe Biden. Since then, he has remained an influential figure in the Republican Party and continues to be active in politics.',NULL,'2024-10-23 17:11:53'),(170,NULL,217,'Joe Biden, born on November 20, 1942, in Scranton, Pennsylvania, is the 46th president of the United States. Before his presidency, Biden had a long career in public service, including serving as a U.S. Senator from Delaware from 1973 to 2009 and as the 47th vice president under Barack Obama from 2009 to 2017. He graduated from the University of Delaware and Syracuse Law School and served on the New Castle County Council before being elected to the Senate at the age of 29.\n\nBiden\'s presidency, which began in 2021, has been marked by efforts to address the COVID-19 pandemic, economic recovery, and significant legislative achievements such as the American Rescue Plan and the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act. His administration has also focused on climate change, healthcare, and restoring alliances with international partners. Biden\'s tenure has faced challenges, including the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan and ongoing political polarization.',NULL,'2024-10-23 17:16:30'),(181,NULL,220,'Born on March 31, 1927, in Yuma, Arizona, Chavez grew up in a migrant farm working family, experiencing firsthand the struggle of agricultural laborers. His early years involved constant relocation and harsh working conditions, which later fueled his dedication to advocating for farm worker rights',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:02:19'),(190,NULL,223,'In the late 1930s, Chavez\'s family settled in San Jose, California, where he faced poverty, racism, and poor working conditions. Here, he developed empathy for his fellow farm workers and recognized the need for a systemic change to improve their lives',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:20:13'),(192,NULL,224,'In the early 1950s, Chavez attended community meetings at Our Lady of Guadalupe Church, where he learned about organizing and activism. This experience was foundational, showing him the power of collective action and laying the groundwork for his future leadership',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:26:45'),(193,NULL,225,'In the 1950s, Cesar became active in the Community Service Organization(CSO) in Fresno. He began organizing Hispanic communities, promoting voter registration, and fighting against police brutality, which helped him build the skills he\'d later use to lead the UFW',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:32:38'),(194,NULL,226,'In September 1965, César Chávez and the UFW launched the historic Delano grape strike, rallying thousands of farm workers to protest poor wages and working conditions. This movement brought national attention to the exploitation of farm workers and marked a major milestone in the labor rights movement.',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:39:51'),(195,NULL,227,'In March 1966, Chavez led a 300 mile pilgrimage from Delano to the California State Capitol in Sacramento. This march drew thousands of supporters and attracted widespread media attention, symbolizing the farm workers\' fight for dignity, respect, and fair labor practices.',NULL,'2024-10-29 17:46:17'),(196,NULL,229,'In 1972, Chavez traveled to New York to promote a nationwide boycott of lettuce, drawing support from unions, churches, and activists. This campaign raised awareness of the injustices faced by farm workers and encouraged consumers to support the UFW\'s cause.',NULL,'2024-10-29 18:05:52'),(197,NULL,230,'In the early 1970s, Chavez organized protests against anti-labor legislation in his home state of Arizona, mobilizing workers and activists to demand better treatment and fair labor policies for farmworkers',NULL,'2024-10-29 18:13:03'),(218,NULL,242,'LeBron James was born on December 30, 1984, to Gloria James in Akron. Raised in a challenging environment, his talent and dedication in basketball would ultimately change his life and that of his community.\n\n',NULL,'2024-11-03 16:42:55'),(223,NULL,145,'On a cold December day in 1803, William Clark and the expedition’s recruits set about clearing land and cutting logs for their winter camp. The party spent five months at Camp Dubois making final preparations for their long journey up the Missouri River',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:08:41'),(225,NULL,250,'In 1994 LeBron met Frank Walker, who introduced him to basketball and provided a stable environment',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:34:11'),(227,NULL,252,'LeBron attended St. Vincent-St from 1999 through 2003. Mary High School, where he became a basketball prodigy',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:41:27'),(228,NULL,253,'Featured on the cover of Sports Illustrated the issue came out on Feb. 18, 2002, LeBron gained nationwide fame as \"The Chosen One.\". That cover became one of SI\'s most iconic over the past couple of decades, plastered with the now famous tagline: “The Chosen One.” James actually got a tattoo on his back that reads “Chosen 1”',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:46:41'),(229,NULL,254,'LeBron was the first overall pick in the 2003 NBA Draft, joining the Cleveland Cavaliers',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:51:56'),(230,NULL,255,'In 2004 LeBron won the NBA Rookie of the Year Award after an impressive first season with the Cavaliers',NULL,'2024-11-09 09:56:07'),(231,NULL,256,'LeBron welcomed his first son born on October 6, 2004, Bronny, who would later follow in his footsteps in basketball',NULL,'2024-11-09 10:01:08'),(240,NULL,266,'KarinaAAAAAAAA',NULL,'2024-11-09 15:30:08'),(243,NULL,267,'WINTERRRRRRR',NULL,'2024-11-09 15:31:57'),(244,NULL,264,'In September 1, 1939 the Nazi regime from Germany invaded Poland, marking the start of World War II in Europe',NULL,'2024-11-09 15:33:16'),(245,NULL,268,'On September 3, 1939, Britain declared war on Germany in response to its invasion of Poland, marking the beginning of Britain\'s involvement in World War II. British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain made the historic announcement from London, addressing the nation and signaling Britain\'s commitment to oppose German aggression. This declaration was a crucial moment, indicating Britain\'s determination to honor its alliances and stand against further expansion by Nazi Germany',NULL,'2024-11-09 15:40:13'),(246,NULL,269,'On the same day as Britain, September 3, 1939, France also declared war on Germany following Germany\'s invasion of Poland. The decision was announced from Paris, where French leaders emphasized their duty to protect their Eastern European ally and resist Nazi aggression. This declaration solidified France’s alliance with Britain and Poland, marking its official entry into World War II and setting the stage for military mobilization and the eventual defense of Western Europe.',NULL,'2024-11-09 15:49:00'),(249,NULL,270,'In april 9, 1940 Germany launched an invasion of Oslo, Norway to secure strategic positions in Northern Europe',NULL,'2024-11-09 16:05:08'),(251,NULL,271,'In May 10, 1940 Germany Invades France through Sedan, France the German forces crossed into France, quickly advancing into the country',NULL,'2024-11-09 16:16:48'),(252,NULL,272,'In June 10, 1940 Italy declared war on Britain and France, joining the Axis powers.',NULL,'2024-11-09 16:23:25'),(257,NULL,300,'The Armistice of 22 June 1940 was an agreement between Nazi Germany and the French Third Republic, signed near Compiègne, France. It became effective on June 25, 1940, ending the Battle of France. The agreement led to a German occupation zone in Northern and Western France, leaving the rest under the French regime but under German influence. The signing location was symbolically chosen by Hitler, as it was where the 1918 armistice ending World War I had been signed.',NULL,'2024-11-12 15:27:10'),(259,NULL,301,'The Battle of Britain started on July 10, 1940, and lasted until October 31, 1940. It was a significant military campaign during World War II where the Royal Air Force (RAF) of the United Kingdom defended against large-scale attacks by Nazi Germany\'s air force, the Luftwaffe. The battle was fought entirely in the air over British airspace, including the English Channel and areas around England.\n\nGermany aimed to gain air superiority over Britain to facilitate a potential invasion. The battle included the initial focus on RAF airfields and infrastructure, followed by the Blitz, where the Luftwaffe targeted British cities and civilian areas, including London. During the Blitz, St. Paul\'s Cathedral in London, located at 51.5138° N, 0.0984° W, became a symbol of British resilience, famously surviving the heavy bombings. The RAF\'s successful defense prevented Germany from achieving air superiority, thwarting a potential invasion and marking a crucial turning point in the war.',NULL,'2024-11-12 15:45:32'),(260,NULL,302,'On June 22, 1941 Germany launched Operation Barbarossa. The initial start point of the invasion was Brest, Belarus. This was Germany\'s launch of a massive invasion into the Soviet Union, breaking their non aggression pact.',NULL,'2024-11-12 16:01:23'),(271,NULL,310,'On December 7, 1941, Pearl Harbor in Hawaii was the target of a surprise military strike by the Japanese. This attack began early in the morning, around 7:55 AM, and involved nearly 200 aircraft targeting airfields and battleships. A second wave of attacks continued shortly after, causing significant devastation. The assault led to the deaths of 2,403 U.S. military personnel and civilians, with 1,178 others wounded, and resulted in the destruction of over 180 aircraft and damage to 19 Navy ships. The attack on Pearl Harbor ultimately prompted the United States to enter World War II, marking the day as one of great historical significance.',NULL,'2024-11-12 16:42:17'),(272,NULL,311,'On December 8, 1941, the day after the attack on Pearl Harbor, President Franklin D. Roosevelt delivered his famous \"Day of Infamy\" speech to a joint session of Congress. In this speech, he declared December 7th as \"a date which will live in infamy\" and called for a declaration of war against Japan. Congress responded swiftly, with the Senate voting unanimously in favor of the declaration, and the House of Representatives passing it with only one dissenting vote. President Roosevelt signed the declaration of war that same day, officially bringing the United States into World War II.',NULL,'2024-11-12 16:46:16'),(273,NULL,312,'The Battle of Midway took place from June 4 to June 7, 1942, and was a critical naval confrontation in the Pacific Theater of World War II. The battle occurred near the Midway Atoll, a small group of islands in the Pacific Ocean. The United States Navy, led by Admirals Chester W. Nimitz, Frank J. Fletcher, and Raymond A. Spruance, aimed to defend the atoll against a Japanese attack. The U.S. forces achieved a decisive victory, sinking four Japanese aircraft carriers (Akagi, Kaga, Soryu, and Hiryu) and one heavy cruiser (Mikuma), while losing only one carrier (USS Yorktown). This victory significantly weakened Japan\'s naval power and marked a turning point in the Pacific War, halting Japanese expansion in the region',NULL,'2024-11-12 16:53:30'),(274,NULL,313,'The Battle of Stalingrad was one of the most brutal and pivotal battles of World War II, taking place from August 23, 1942, to February 2, 1943. The battle occurred in the city of Stalingrad (now Volgograd), Russia, and involved intense close-quarters combat and aerial bombardment. The German Army, under the command of General Friedrich Paulus, aimed to capture the city, which was a key industrial center and a symbolic target due to its name bearing that of Soviet leader Joseph Stalin. The Soviet forces, led by Generals Georgy Zhukov and Vasily Chuikov, fiercely defended the city.\n\nThe battle saw some of the fiercest fighting in the war, with both sides suffering heavy casualties. The Soviet Union launched a successful counteroffensive in mid-November 1942, encircling the German 6th Army and trapping over 220,000 soldiers. By February 1943, the remaining German forces, numbering around 91,000, were forced to surrender.\n\nThe Battle of Stalingrad marked a turning point in the war on the Eastern Front, as it halted the German advance into the Soviet Union and began the pushback that would eventually lead to the fall of Nazi Germany.',NULL,'2024-11-12 16:56:27'),(275,NULL,314,'D-Day, also known as the Normandy Invasion, took place on June 6, 1944. This massive operation involved Allied forces, including American, British, and Canadian troops, launching an amphibious assault on the beaches of Normandy, France. The primary objective was to liberate German-occupied Western Europe and establish a new front against Nazi Germany. Despite facing strong German defenses and heavy casualties, the Allied forces successfully secured the beaches, which were codenamed Utah, Omaha, Gold, Juno, and Sword. The successful landings marked a significant turning point in World War II, as they paved the way for the liberation of France and the eventual defeat of Nazi Germany. By the end of August 1944, all of northern France was liberated, contributing to the downfall of Nazi control in Western Europe.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:02:50'),(276,NULL,315,'The Battle of Leyte Gulf took place from October 23 to October 26, 1944, and was the largest naval battle of World War II. It occurred in the waters around the Philippine island of Leyte and involved the United States and Australia against Japan. The battle was part of the Allied invasion of the Philippines and aimed to cut off Japan\'s supply lines to the East Indies and provide bases for an attack on the Japanese home islands. The U.S. Navy\'s Third and Seventh Fleets played a crucial role in repulsing the Japanese forces, which included kamikaze attacks. The battle resulted in heavy losses for the Japanese Navy, crippling their Combined Fleet and reinforcing Allied control of the Pacific.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:06:41'),(277,NULL,316,'The Battle of the Bulge, also known as the Battle of the Ardennes, was the last major German offensive on the Western Front during World War II. It took place from December 16, 1944, to January 16, 1945. The Germans launched a surprise attack in the densely forested Ardennes region of Belgium, aiming to split the Allied forces and capture the vital port of Antwerp. The battle got its name from the \"bulge\" that appeared in the Allied front lines as German forces pushed forward.\n\nDespite initial successes, the German advance was eventually halted by strong Allied resistance and reinforcements. The battle was fought under harsh winter conditions, with freezing temperatures and heavy snowfall adding to the difficulties faced by both sides. The Allies suffered significant casualties, including many Americans killed. The Germans also incurred heavy losses.\n\nThe Battle of the Bulge marked the end of Germany\'s major offensive capabilities on the Western Front and paved the way for the Allied advance into Germany, leading to the eventual defeat of Nazi Germany.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:11:42'),(278,NULL,317,'dolf Hitler, the dictator of Nazi Germany, died on April 30, 1945, in his underground bunker in Berlin. As Soviet troops closed in on the city, Hitler committed suicide by shooting himself in the head. His wife, Eva Braun, whom he had married just a day earlier, also took her own life by ingesting cyanide. Following Hitler\'s instructions, their bodies were carried outside, doused in petrol, and set on fire to prevent them from being captured by the advancing Soviet forces. The news of Hitler\'s death was announced on German radio the next day, marking a significant moment in the closing stages of World War II.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:15:01'),(279,NULL,318,'Germany\'s surrender in World War II was formalized on May 7, 1945, when General Alfred Jodl of the German High Command signed the unconditional surrender of all German forces at Reims, in northeastern France. This surrender was later ratified on May 8, 1945, in Berlin, Germany, to satisfy the Soviet Union\'s demand for a separate signing. The signing in Berlin took place at the seat of the Soviet Military Administration, marking the official end of World War II in Europe',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:21:27'),(280,NULL,319,'On August 6, 1945, during World War II, the United States dropped an atomic bomb on the Japanese city of Hiroshima. The bomb, nicknamed \"Little Boy,\" was carried by the B-29 bomber Enola Gay and detonated at approximately 8:15 AM. The explosion had a devastating impact, instantly killing an estimated 80,000 people and causing widespread destruction. In the following weeks and months, tens of thousands more died from injuries and radiation exposure. The bombing of Hiroshima, along with the subsequent bombing of Nagasaki, played a significant role in Japan\'s decision to surrender, effectively bringing an end to World War II',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:25:23'),(281,NULL,320,'On August 9, 1945, the United States dropped an atomic bomb on the Japanese city of Nagasaki. The bomb, nicknamed \"Fat Man,\" was carried by the B-29 bomber Bockscar and detonated at approximately 11:02 AM. The explosion had a devastating impact, instantly killing an estimated 40,000 people and causing widespread destruction. In the following weeks and months, tens of thousands more died from injuries and radiation exposure. The bombing of Nagasaki, along with the previous bombing of Hiroshima, played a significant role in Japan\'s decision to surrender, effectively bringing an end to World War II.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:29:22'),(282,NULL,321,'Japan\'s surrender in World War II was announced by Emperor Hirohito on August 15, 1945, and formally signed on September 2, 1945. The signing took place aboard the American battleship USS Missouri in Tokyo Bay. This event marked the official end of World War II, with representatives from Japan and the Allied nations, including the United States, China, the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union, Australia, Canada, France, the Netherlands, and New Zealand, present to witness the ceremony.',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:36:57'),(283,NULL,322,'LeBron James won his first Olympic gold medal with the USA basketball team at the Beijing 2008 Olympic Games. He was a key player on the \"Redeem Team,\" which aimed to reclaim the gold medal after the USA\'s bronze finish in Athens 2004. LeBron\'s performance in Beijing was instrumental in the team\'s success, and they defeated Spain in the gold medal game to secure the top spot on the podium',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:45:43'),(284,NULL,323,'In June 14,2007 LeBron\'s second son was born at Hill crest Hospital he was named Bryce Maximus James',NULL,'2024-11-12 17:51:36'),(285,NULL,324,'LeBron James proposed to Savannah Brinson on New Year\'s Eve 2011, just after midnight. He had his friend and teammate, Dwyane Wade, hold the ring for him until the big moment',NULL,'2024-11-12 18:12:08'),(286,NULL,328,'LeBron James won his first NBA championship with the Miami Heat in 2012. The Heat defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder in the 2012 NBA Finals, winning the series 4-1. LeBron was named Finals MVP, averaging 28.6 points, 10.2 rebounds, and 7.4 assists per game during the series.',NULL,'2024-11-12 18:20:44'),(287,NULL,329,'LeBron James won his second NBA championship with the Miami Heat in 2013. The Heat defeated the San Antonio Spurs in the 2013 NBA Finals, winning the series 4-3. LeBron was named Finals MVP for the second consecutive year, averaging 25.3 points, 10.9 rebounds, and 7 assists per game during the series. The victory came after a dramatic Game 6 that went into overtime, and a solid performance in Game 7 where LeBron scored 37 points.',NULL,'2024-11-12 18:24:52'),(288,NULL,330,'LeBron James and Savannah Brinson got married on September 14, 2013, in a lavish ceremony at the Grand Del Mar resort in San Diego, California. The event was attended by around 200 guests, including LeBron\'s teammate Dwyane Wade and his then-girlfriend Gabrielle Union, as well as other NBA players like Chris Paul and Carmelo Anthony.',NULL,'2024-11-12 18:26:42');
